'''Langrick''' is a small village  in the [[East Lindsey]] [[Non-metropolitan district|district]] of [[Lincolnshire]], England. It is situated in the [[civil parish]] of [[Langriville]], and on the [[B1192 road]], {{Convert|5|mi|km|0}} north-west from [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]]. The village lies in the Lincolnshire [[The Fens|Fens]], and less than {{Convert|1|mi|km|1}} east from the [[River Witham]].
 
==History==
The name Langrick appears to come from "Long Creek"<ref>{{cite book|title=The History & Antiquities of Boston|year=1856|publisher=Longman & Co|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3Wg1AQAAIAAJ|author=[[Pishey Thompson]]|accessdate=8 February 2012|page=360}}</ref>  and is at the very southern edge of Wildmore Fen, in an area which was once the manor of Armtree, in the parish of [[Coningsby]].<ref name="PT">{{cite book|title=The History & Antiquities of Boston|year=1856|publisher=Longman & Co|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3Wg1AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA622|author=[[Pishey Thompson]]|accessdate=8 February 2012|page=622}}</ref>  It was once the site of a hermitage belonging to [[Kirkstead Abbey]]. 
When Langrick and Langriville were [[enclosure|enclosed]] in 1812 there was not a single house existing.<ref name='Boston'>{{cite web|title=Boston UK|url=http://www.bostonuk.com/historydetail.php?id=634&f=Boston|work=Langrick|publisher=Visitor uk.com|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> Langrick's importance was that it was the site of a ferry crossing over the River Witham,<ref name="Boston"/> reputedly built by [[Robert Dymoke]].<ref name="PT"/> The river was straightened in 1833.<ref name="Boston"/>

A steel bridge was built just west of the ferry site in 1909<ref name="Boston"/> and is still in use today.

==Church==
[[File:Langrick church.jpg|thumb|280x|left|St Margaret's Church, Langrick]]
[[Saint Margaret of Scotland]] Church was built in 1828,<ref name="Boston"/> probably by Jeptha Pacey, but was not [[Dedication#Dedication of churches|dedicated]] until 20 April 1922.<ref name=Langriville>{{cite web|title=Langriville Parish Council Website|url=http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Langriville/section.asp?catId=14392|accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> It is a Grade II [[listed building]] and was restored and altered in 1885.<ref>{{cite web|title=St Margaret, Langrick|url=http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1359725|work=National Heritage List for England|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref> 
The registers of births and deaths date from 1831, and those of marriages from 1837.<ref name="Langriville"/> The church was restored again and redecorated in 1935, and further work was carried out in 1968.<ref name="Langriville"/>

Today, the church forms part of the Brothertoft Group, in the [[Diocese of Lincoln]], also known as 'Five in the Fen', which also includes:<ref>{{cite web|title=A Church Near You|url=http://www.achurchnearyou.com/langrick-st-margaret-of-scotland/|publisher=A Church Near You|accessdate=26 April 2011}}</ref> 
*St Gilbert of Sempringham, [[Brothertoft]]
*All Saints, [[Holland Fen]]
*Christ Church, [[Kirton Holme]]
*St Peter, [[Wildmore]]

==Railway station==
[[Langrick railway station]] was on the now dismantled [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]] railway line between [[Lincoln, England|Lincoln]] and [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]].<ref name="Boston"/> A cafe stands on the site of the station master's house and booking office.<ref>{{cite web|title=Langrick|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/l/langrick/index.shtml|work=Disused Stations|publisher=Subterranea Brittanica|accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref> 

The Water Rail Way follows the route of the old dismantled [[railway line]] from Lincoln to Boston and can be joined at Langrick.<ref>{{cite web|title=Water Rail Way|url=http://www.sustrans.org.uk/sustrans-near-you/midlands/easy-rides-in-the-midlands/water-rail-way|publisher=Sustrans Org|accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref>

Near the site of the old railway line is the Ferry Boat Inn [[public house]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ferry Boat Inn|url=http://www.information-britain.co.uk/showPlace.cfm?Place_ID=36711|publisher=Information Britain|accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref> 

